success.question_text: How much soil would be moved in a minute?
success.question_hint:
• There are 60 minutes in an hour.
  • Change the tonnes to kilograms before dividing.

stimulus_2.text: Soil is being moved at a building site at the rate of 36 tonnes per hour.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Work logically, step by step, when converting a rate.

success.question_text: What is the ratio of 20 minutes to 3 hours in simplest form?
success.question_hint:
• There are 60 minutes in an hour.
  • Simplify the ratio by dividing each by the highest common factor.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A ratio involves two or more quantities that, when simplified, must be expressed with the same units. For example, a ratio of 20 minutes to 3 hours is not 20:3.

success.question_text:
What is the total weight, in kilograms, of the packed box?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2 kg type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• There are 12 in a dozen.
  • Find the combined mass of the bottles and add the mass of the cardboard box.

stimulus_2.text: A cardboard box weighs 170 g. It is to be packed with a dozen bottles of drink each weighing 1.2 kg.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

One dozen is twelve. 1 kg = 1000 g.

success.question_text: What is the area of the pentagonal face of prism Q?
success.question_hint:
• The volume of a prism is V = Ah, where A is the area of the cross-section and h is the height of the prism.
  • Use division to find the height of the hexagonal prism and use the answer to find the volume of the pentagonal prism.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of any prism is found by multiplying the area of the cross-section by the perpendicular height.

review_7.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of any prism is found by multiplying the area of the cross-section by the perpendicular height.

success.question_text: What is the area of this shape?
success.question_hint:
• The area is found using half the height times the sum of the two parallel sides.
  • There is one measurement on the diagram that is not used to find the area.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

A trapezium is a plane figure with one pair of parallel sides. The ‘height’ of a trapezium is the distance between the parallel sides.

success.question_text: What was the average time Chloe spent working of an afternoon?
success.question_hint:
• Find the mean by adding the times and dividing by the number of days.
  • Change the decimal answer into hours and minutes.

stimulus_1.text: Chloe recorded the amount of time spent working after school on four afternoons one week:

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Take care with time. For example, 0.25 h is one-quarter of an hour or 15 minutes.

success.question_text:
What is the area of the rectangle?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2 m2 type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• If b = breadth, then length = 2b and the perimeter is 6b.
  • Solve the equation 6b = 42 to find the breadth b, and the length and then the area.

stimulus_1.text: The perimeter of a rectangle is 42 metres. The length is twice the breadth.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Where possible, check that a solution to a problem actually works. For example, in this question make a quick mental check that a length of 14 m and a breadth of 7 m does give a perimeter of 42 m.

success.question_text:
Jack uses the online ruler to determine the scale used in the drawing.

He uses this scale to find the width of the paddock and then found the area of the paddock.

What is the area in square metres?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2 m2 type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• Use the ruler to determine the scale used in the drawing.
  • Find the width of the paddock and then the area by multiplying.

stimulus_1.text: The rectangular paddock below is drawn to scale:

review_2.column_1_text:
The length of the rectangle is 12 cm.

This means 12 cm = 180 m, and so 1 cm = 15 m.

The width of the rectangle is 8 cm, and using the scale, the width of the paddock is 8 × 15 = 120 m.

The dimensions of the paddock are 180 m by 120 m.

 Area = 180 × 120
      = 21 600

The area is 21 600 m2.

Tip

Determine the scale used on the known side to find the missing side.

success.question_text:
How many metres will it travel in one second at this speed?

Type the number in the box, not the unit of measurement, e.g. for 2 m type 2.
success.question_hint:
• Change 252 kilometres to metres.
  • Divide to find the distance in one minute, and then divide again to find the distance in one second.

stimulus_2.text: A racing car can travel at 252 km/h.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Work logically, step by step, when converting a rate.

success.question_text: Which is the best estimate for the length of the diagonal of the square?
success.question_hint:
• Work out the length of each side in the square.
  • Use Pythagoras’ theorem to find the length of the diagonal.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Pythagoras’ theorem states that in any right-angled triangle the square on the hypotenuse is equal to the sum of the squares on the other two sides.

success.question_text:
How much did the temperature rise during the day?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2° type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• The rise in temperature is the difference between the two temperatures.
  • Use the (–) button on your calculator when entering a negative number.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Make sure you can work with negative numbers.

success.question_hint:
• You can use the formula Circumference equals 2 times pi times the radius.
  • Another formula is Circumference equals pi times the diameter but make sure you double the length of the radius to give the diameter.

stimulus_1.text: The radius of a circle is 4.9 m.

success.question_text: How many of these cups can be filled from a four-litre container?
success.question_hint:
• Change 4 litres to millilitres.
  • Divide your answer by the size of each cup to find the number of cups that can be filled.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Take care when rounding off that it is a logical thing to do. For example, this question asks how many cups can be filled. Although the answer is closer to 18 than 17, only 17 cups can actually be filled.

success.question_text:
What is the volume of this solid?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2 m3 type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• Find the area of the front face by splitting it into two rectangles.
  • The volume of a prism is given as V = Ah, where A is the area of the cross-section (face) and h is the height (or thickness).

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of any prism is found by multiplying the area of the cross-section by the perpendicular height.

success.question_text:
What is the area of all the surfaces of this prism?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 23 m2 type only 23.
success.question_hint:
• There are five faces to the prism.
  • Find the area of the front and then double, the area of the side, and double, and then add the area of the base.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

To find the total surface area of a prism, you need to find the area of every face.

success.question_text:
What is the area to be paved?

Type the number, not the unit of measurement, in the box, e.g. for 2 m2 type only 2.
success.question_hint:
• You need to find the area between the larger rectangle and the smaller rectangle.
  • The length and width of the larger rectangle is 2 metres added on to the dimensions of the smaller rectangle.

stimulus_1.text: A rectangular swimming pool is 8 m long and 5 m wide. An area 1 metre wide around the pool is to be paved.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Often an easy way to find a composite area is to find the difference between a large and small area.
